metrics.title: First Contentful Paint
metrics.description: First Contentful Paint marks the time at which the first text or image is painted. [Learn more about the First Contentful Paint metric](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/first-contentful-paint/).

metrics.title: Speed Index
metrics.description: Speed Index shows how quickly the contents of a page are visibly populated. [Learn more about the Speed Index metric](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/speed-index/).

metrics.title: Total Blocking Time
metrics.description: Sum of all time periods between FCP and Time to Interactive, when task length exceeded 50ms, expressed in milliseconds. [Learn more about the Total Blocking Time metric](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/lighthouse-total-blocking-time/).

metrics.title: Largest Contentful Paint
metrics.description: Largest Contentful Paint marks the time at which the largest text or image is painted. [Learn more about the Largest Contentful Paint metric](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/lighthouse-largest-contentful-paint/)

metrics.title: Cumulative Layout Shift
metrics.description: Cumulative Layout Shift measures the movement of visible elements within the viewport. [Learn more about the Cumulative Layout Shift metric](https://web.dev/articles/cls).

audits.name: Eliminate render-blocking resources
audits.description: Resources are blocking the first paint of your page. Consider delivering critical JS/CSS inline and deferring all non-critical JS/styles. [Learn how to eliminate render-blocking resources](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/render-blocking-resources/).

settings.name: Critical CSS
settings.description: Extract and prioritize above-the-fold CSS.

inputs.control_label: Remove Critical CSS on User Interaction

settings.name: Self Host Google Fonts
settings.description: Self host all your Google fonts and load fonts faster. Turn on CDN to serve these fonts faster through RapidLoad CDN.

settings.name: Defer Javascript
settings.description: Render-blocking JS on website can be resolved with defer javaScript.

audits.name: Properly size images
audits.description: Serve images that are appropriately-sized to save cellular data and improve load time. [Learn how to size images](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/uses-responsive-images/).

settings.name: Serve next-gen Images (AVIF, WEBP)
settings.description: Serve the images in next-gen image formats to all the browsers that support them.

inputs.control_label: Exclude Images from modern image urls

audits.name: Defer offscreen images
audits.description: Consider lazy-loading offscreen and hidden images after all critical resources have finished loading to lower time to interactive. [Learn how to defer offscreen images](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/offscreen-images/).

settings.name: Lazy Load Images
settings.description: Delay loading of images until needed.

audits.name: Minify CSS
audits.description: Minifying CSS files can reduce network payload sizes. [Learn how to minify CSS](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/unminified-css/).

settings.name: Minify CSS
settings.description: Remove unnecessary spaces, lines and comments from CSS files.

audits.name: Minify JavaScript
audits.description: Minifying JavaScript files can reduce payload sizes and script parse time. [Learn how to minify JavaScript](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/unminified-javascript/).

settings.name: Minify Javascript
settings.description: Remove unnecessary spaces, lines and comments from JS files.

inputs.control_label: Exclude js files from being minify

audits.name: Reduce unused CSS
audits.description: Reduce unused rules from stylesheets and defer CSS not used for above-the-fold content to decrease bytes consumed by network activity. [Learn how to reduce unused CSS](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/unused-css-rules/).

settings.name: Remove Unused CSS
settings.description: Remove unused CSS for each page and reduce page size.

audits.name: Reduce unused JavaScript
audits.description: Reduce unused JavaScript and defer loading scripts until they are required to decrease bytes consumed by network activity. [Learn how to reduce unused JavaScript](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/unused-javascript/).

settings.name: Delay Javascript
settings.description: Loading JS files on user interaction

audits.name: Efficiently encode images
audits.description: Optimized images load faster and consume less cellular data. [Learn how to efficiently encode images](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/uses-optimized-images/).

settings.name: Serve next-gen Images (AVIF, WEBP)
settings.description: Serve the images in next-gen image formats to all the browsers that support them.

inputs.control_label: Exclude Images from modern image urls

audits.name: Serve images in next-gen formats
audits.description: Image formats like WebP and AVIF often provide better compression than PNG or JPEG, which means faster downloads and less data consumption. [Learn more about modern image formats](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/uses-webp-images/).

settings.name: Serve next-gen Images (AVIF, WEBP)
settings.description: Serve the images in next-gen image formats to all the browsers that support them.

inputs.control_label: Exclude Images from modern image urls

audits.name: Enable text compression
audits.description: Text-based resources should be served with compression (gzip, deflate or brotli) to minimize total network bytes. [Learn more about text compression](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/uses-text-compression/).

audits.name: Preconnect to required origins
audits.description: Consider adding `preconnect` or `dns-prefetch` resource hints to establish early connections to important third-party origins. [Learn how to preconnect to required origins](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/uses-rel-preconnect/).

audits.name: Reduce initial server response time
audits.description: Keep the server response time for the main document short because all other requests depend on it. [Learn more about the Time to First Byte metric](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/time-to-first-byte/).

settings.name: Page Cache
settings.description: Optimize and cache static HTML pages to provide a snappier page experience.

settings.name: Preload Links
settings.description: Preload Links

settings.name: Disable WP-Emojis
settings.description: Prevents WordPress from displaying emojis, smiley faces and other icons

audits.name: Avoid multiple page redirects
audits.description: Redirects introduce additional delays before the page can be loaded. [Learn how to avoid page redirects](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/redirects/).

audits.name: Use video formats for animated content
audits.description: Large GIFs are inefficient for delivering animated content. Consider using MPEG4/WebM videos for animations and PNG/WebP for static images instead of GIF to save network bytes. [Learn more about efficient video formats](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/efficient-animated-content/)

audits.name: Remove duplicate modules in JavaScript bundles
audits.description: Remove large, duplicate JavaScript modules from bundles to reduce unnecessary bytes consumed by network activity.

audits.name: Avoid serving legacy JavaScript to modern browsers
audits.description: Polyfills and transforms enable legacy browsers to use new JavaScript features. However, many aren't necessary for modern browsers. For your bundled JavaScript, adopt a modern script deployment strategy using module/nomodule feature detection to reduce the amount of code shipped to modern browsers, while retaining support for legacy browsers. [Learn how to use modern JavaScript](https://web.dev/articles/publish-modern-javascript)

audits.name: Avoids enormous network payloads
audits.description: Large network payloads cost users real money and are highly correlated with long load times. [Learn how to reduce payload sizes](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/total-byte-weight/).

audits.name: Serve static assets with an efficient cache policy
audits.description: A long cache lifetime can speed up repeat visits to your page. [Learn more about efficient cache policies](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/uses-long-cache-ttl/).

settings.name: RapidLoad CDN
settings.description: Load resource files faster by using 112 edge locations with only 27ms latency.

settings.name: Cache Policy
settings.description: Set up cache-control header to increase the browser cache expiration

audits.name: Avoids an excessive DOM size
audits.description: A large DOM will increase memory usage, cause longer [style calculations](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/performance/rendering/reduce-the-scope-and-complexity-of-style-calculations), and produce costly [layout reflows](https://developers.google.com/speed/articles/reflow). [Learn how to avoid an excessive DOM size](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/dom-size/).

audits.name: User Timing marks and measures
audits.description: Consider instrumenting your app with the User Timing API to measure your app's real-world performance during key user experiences. [Learn more about User Timing marks](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/user-timings/).

audits.name: JavaScript execution time
audits.description: Consider reducing the time spent parsing, compiling, and executing JS. You may find delivering smaller JS payloads helps with this. [Learn how to reduce Javascript execution time](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/bootup-time/).

settings.name: Delay Javascript
settings.description: Loading JS files on user interaction

audits.name: Minimizes main-thread work
audits.description: Consider reducing the time spent parsing, compiling and executing JS. You may find delivering smaller JS payloads helps with this. [Learn how to minimize main-thread work](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/mainthread-work-breakdown/)

audits.name: Ensure text remains visible during webfont load
audits.description: Leverage the `font-display` CSS feature to ensure text is user-visible while webfonts are loading. [Learn more about `font-display`](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/font-display/).

settings.name: Self Host Google Fonts
settings.description: Self host all your Google fonts and load fonts faster. Turn on CDN to serve these fonts faster through RapidLoad CDN.

audits.name: Minimize third-party usage
audits.description: Third-party code can significantly impact load performance. Limit the number of redundant third-party providers and try to load third-party code after your page has primarily finished loading. [Learn how to minimize third-party impact](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/performance/optimizing-content-efficiency/loading-third-party-javascript/).
audits.displayValue: Third-party code blocked the main thread for 0 ms

audits.name: Lazy load third-party resources with facades
audits.description: Some third-party embeds can be lazy loaded. Consider replacing them with a facade until they are required. [Learn how to defer third-parties with a facade](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/third-party-facades/).

settings.name: Lazy Load Iframes
settings.description: Delay loading of iframes until needed.

audits.name: Largest Contentful Paint image was not lazily loaded
audits.description: Above-the-fold images that are lazily loaded render later in the page lifecycle, which can delay the largest contentful paint. [Learn more about optimal lazy loading](https://web.dev/articles/lcp-lazy-loading).

settings.name: Exclude Above-the-fold Images from Lazy Load
settings.description: Improve your LCP images.

inputs.control_label: Exclude LCP image from Lazy Load
Exclude Above-the-fold Images from Lazy Load

audits.name: Uses passive listeners to improve scrolling performance
audits.description: Consider marking your touch and wheel event listeners as `passive` to improve your page's scroll performance. [Learn more about adopting passive event listeners](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/best-practices/uses-passive-event-listeners/).

audits.name: Avoids `document.write()`
audits.description: For users on slow connections, external scripts dynamically injected via `document.write()` can delay page load by tens of seconds. [Learn how to avoid document.write()](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/best-practices/no-document-write/).

audits.name: Avoid long main-thread tasks
audits.description: Lists the longest tasks on the main thread, useful for identifying worst contributors to input delay. [Learn how to avoid long main-thread tasks](https://web.dev/articles/optimize-long-tasks)

audits.name: Avoid non-composited animations
audits.description: Animations which are not composited can be janky and increase CLS. [Learn how to avoid non-composited animations](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/non-composited-animations/)

audits.name: Image elements do not have explicit `width` and `height`
audits.description: Set an explicit width and height on image elements to reduce layout shifts and improve CLS. [Learn how to set image dimensions](https://web.dev/articles/optimize-cls#images_without_dimensions)

settings.description: Include width and height attributes for these images.

inputs.control_label: Exclude Images from being set width and height

audits.name: Has a `<meta name="viewport">` tag with `width` or `initial-scale`
audits.description: A `<meta name="viewport">` not only optimizes your app for mobile screen sizes, but also prevents [a 300 millisecond delay to user input](https://developer.chrome.com/blog/300ms-tap-delay-gone-away/). [Learn more about using the viewport meta tag](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/pwa/viewport/).

audits.name: Avoid chaining critical requests
audits.description: The Critical Request Chains below show you what resources are loaded with a high priority. Consider reducing the length of chains, reducing the download size of resources, or deferring the download of unnecessary resources to improve page load. [Learn how to avoid chaining critical requests](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/critical-request-chains/).

audits.name: Resources Summary
audits.description: Aggregates all network requests and groups them by type

audits.name: Largest Contentful Paint element
audits.description: This is the largest contentful element painted within the viewport. [Learn more about the Largest Contentful Paint element](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/lighthouse/performance/lighthouse-largest-contentful-paint/)

audits.name: Preload Largest Contentful Paint image
audits.description: If the LCP element is dynamically added to the page, you should preload the image in order to improve LCP. [Learn more about preloading LCP elements](https://web.dev/articles/optimize-lcp#optimize_when_the_resource_is_discovered).
